WEBVTT

00:00:00.640 --> 00:00:05.440
And this again is one of the best parts about Posit Workbench, is that no matter what your

00:00:05.440 --> 00:00:11.120
data science team uses, their preferred IDE, the hope is that we can support it here within Posit

00:00:11.120 --> 00:00:16.400
Workbench. So we currently support Jupyter Notebook, JupyterLab, we have the rstudio IDE as

00:00:16.400 --> 00:00:21.360
well, and then we have the VS Code Editor, which is a great all-purpose editor, which is what we're

00:00:21.360 --> 00:00:27.120
going to use today. So I'm going to click on VS Code, and when we do that we get some additional

00:00:27.120 --> 00:00:32.480
options. So I can give this VS Code session a name, I'll just leave it as a default right here,

00:00:33.279 --> 00:00:38.400
and then right underneath you're going to see Cluster Kubernetes. Now to tell you a little bit

00:00:38.400 --> 00:00:43.919
more about our demo environment here at Posit, it is all hosted in AWS, Amazon Web Services,

00:00:44.639 --> 00:00:49.840
and it's in a high performance computing cluster, an HPC environment, and that environment is

00:00:49.840 --> 00:00:54.639
managed using something known as Kubernetes. So some of you may have heard of Kubernetes, that's

00:00:54.639 --> 00:01:00.720
one of these HPC managers that we support. If you also use Slurm, we can support that as well.

00:01:01.279 --> 00:01:04.959
Or you can also just run these tools on a single server, that's totally fine as well.

00:01:05.760 --> 00:01:13.440
But one of the advantages of using Kubernetes or Slurm is you can actually control this job's CPU

00:01:13.440 --> 00:01:18.879
and memory allocations. So if you just have like a small job, you want to maybe create a plot or a

00:01:18.879 --> 00:01:24.320
simple application, you can keep the CPU low, keep the memory low, and that's just great for managing

00:01:24.320 --> 00:01:30.639
compute resources. But if you have a higher compute, a more demanding job, I can bump that up,

00:01:30.639 --> 00:01:35.279
for example, I can change the memory as well. So really good at managing resources.

00:01:36.480 --> 00:01:41.839
Then you'll see this last box right here, and this is the image box. So I have the option to

00:01:41.839 --> 00:01:47.760
choose a specific Docker image here to deploy this session. So that can help control additional

00:01:47.760 --> 00:01:53.760
environment variables, things like what R versions are available, Python versions,

00:01:53.760 --> 00:01:58.800
what packages are installed by default, that can all be controlled using various Docker images.

00:01:58.800 --> 00:02:03.519
But I'll just stick with the default for right now. That all looks good. Let's go ahead and

00:02:03.519 --> 00:02:04.400
start the session.

